Here’s a ready-to-use .gitignore for a Node.js project.
It will ignore node_modules, logs, environment files, build artifacts, and other common Node.js-generated files.
Gitignore# Node.js dependencies
node_modules/
npm-debug.log*
yarn-debug.log*
yarn-error.log*
pnpm-debug.log*

# Environment variables
.env
.env.test
.env.production
.env.local

# Logs
logs
*.log
*.log.*

# Runtime data
pids
*.pid
*.seed
*.pid.lock

# Coverage reports
coverage/
*.lcov

# Build output
dist/
build/
tmp/
temp/

# OS-specific files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# IDE/editor settings
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp

# Optional npm cache directory
.npm

# Optional eslint cache
.eslintcache

# Optional REPL history
.node_repl_history

# Optional package lock files (if not using them)
# package-lock.json
# yarn.lock
# pnpm-lock.yaml

How to use:

Create a .gitignore file in your project root (if it doesn’t exist).
Paste the above content into it.
Run:Bashgit rm -r --cached node_modules
git commit -m "Update .gitignore to exclude node_modules and other files"



This ensures node_modules and other unnecessary files are never committed to your Git repository.

If you want, I can give you a minimal .gitignore just for Node.js essentials without extra entries.
